While senior Bush administration officials repeatedly have denied pursuing new nuclear weapons by saying the military has not defined a formal need for them, arms-control activists said Assistant Defense Secretary Dale Klein recently confirmed that he is seeking &quot;sign-off&quot; inside the Pentagon for a new, nuclear &quot;bunker buster.&quot; <br>
<br>
Speaking March 19 in his office, Klein said he expects to produce a full military requirement for the &quot;robust nuclear earth penetrator&quot; in &quot;a month or months,&quot; according to activists at the meeting. <br>
<br>
The secret Pentagon document would lay out meticulous specifications for weapons scientists in California and New Mexico to meet in designing the nation's first modern nuclear weapon intended for post-Cold War targets. <br>
<br>
Defense officials and Republican lawmakers argue that such a bunker buster offers the prospect of decapitating Third World dictatorships or disarming them of chemical, biological or nuclear arse-nals with single H-bombs inside a tough, hardened-steel case. <br>
<br>
&quot;You have to have the ability to go after the leaders of a military activity against the United States,&quot; said Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-San Diego, chairman of the House Armed Services Committee. &quot;Having the ability to have bunker-buster capability is an important aspect of deterrence. You must have that capability.&quot; <br>
<br>
While Congress has talked of low-yield weapons -- exploding perhaps a few hundred tons of TNT equivalent and so limiting collateral damage -- the robust nuclear earth penetrator is likely to be a bomb of high explosive yield. <br>
<br>
&quot;This is part of the Bush administration's policy shift to pre-emptive strikes, and it destabilizes an already volatile world,&quot; said Marylia Kelley, executive director of Tri-Valley CAREs, a Livermore lab watchdog group. &quot;We're telling other nations to abandon all programs to develop weapons of mass destruction. But I think it's counter to our nonproliferation goals to develop new weapons and the policy to use them first against non-nuclear states.&quot; <br>
<br>
Senior weapons scientists and Energy Department officials say the weapon would be based on Los Alamos' B61, Lawrence Livermore's B83, or both. <br>
<br>
Computer simulations performed by nongovernment analysts suggest that such a weapon, even encased in the hardest steel, would not plow more than 60 feet in rock or hard soil -- coincidentally close to the ideal depth for digging large craters and creating clouds of radioactive fallout. <br>
<br>
Klein hinted that some military leaders are not fully behind the new weapon. He declined activists' offers to supply independent scientists' views on the utility of the new weapon, saying, &quot;That's OK. We have enough diversity of opinion already.&quot; <br>
<br>
Pentagon and Energy Department officials wanted design teams at Livermore and Los Alamos to start working on the weapon last year. But Democrats questioned the practical military use of the weapon and insisted on Congress first getting a report on the need for the weapon, its potential targets and an assessment of conventional methods for dealing with those targets. <br>
<br>
The Bush administration delivered the classified report to House and Senate armed services committees on the eve of war with Iraq, starting a 30-day clock on the release of funds for designing the weapon. <br>
<br>
Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Alamo, and Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., have led opposition to the weapon in the House. <br>
<br>
&quot;They may ask us for the development of RNEP and we will fight it,&quot; Spratt said. Lawmakers were briefed this week on the Pentagon report, and Democrat opponents are &quot;getting together people to take up the argument against it.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;It's not clear that conventional weapons couldn't handle the threat of underground bunkers just as well as nuclear weapons,&quot; Spratt said. <br>
<br>
Some observers predict an uphill battle. &quot;My guess is this is going to happen. Folks have been beating the drum on this for a while. The political environment is kind of wrong for people opposing it,&quot; said University of Maryland physicist Steve Fetter, vice chairman of the board for the Federation of American Scientists. <br>
<br>
Congress still would have to approve production of the weapon. But the move inside the Pentagon for a full military requirement reflects a firmer administration resolve to actually develop the bomb, not merely researching potential designs.<br>
<br>
Washington Bureau reporter Lisa Friedman contributed to this report.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Typically, a requirement for such a weapon will be a notebook-size document that lists the MCs -- the military characteristics. They are the desired explosive yields (many U.S. nuclear weapons offer variable yield), weight, size, delivery aircraft, the depth of penetration, the kind of &quot;permissive action link&quot; (a system for guarding against unauthorized detonation of a weapon.) It also includes the conditions in which the weapon must operate, from storage to flight at subzero temperatures to crashing through tons of rock, details known as the STS, or stockpile-to-target sequence parameters. <br>
<br>
The last time the Pentagon issued a military requirement was in 1995, for the B61 Mod 11, a nuclear earth penetrator weighing more than half a ton. <br>
<br>
Even though the Cold War was over, the B61-11 still was designed for missile silos and other &quot;counterforce&quot; targets in the former Soviet Union and China. <br>
<br>
Teams at Los Alamos and Sandia anchored the B61's nuclear explosive inside a tougher steel case and nose cone, left off the parachute, changed the fuse and added fins and other features. The end result was a conversion kit shipped off to Air Force bases starting in December 1996. The bomb is thought to have limited penetration, a deficiency that scientists aim to double with the new weapon. <br>
<br>
Robert S. Norris, a senior analyst at the Natural Resources Defense Council, and Hans M. Kristensen, a private researcher in the East Bay, estimate 50 B61s were converted, all stored at Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo., home of the Stealth bomber wing.<br>
